  <title>Week 3 Assignment</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Write the first vector as a linear combination of the second
        and third vectors or show that it cannot be done.(8)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <me>
              \begin{pmatrix}
                2 \\ 7 
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                -1 \\ 1 
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                4  \\ 3 
              \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \begin{pmatrix}
                1 \\ 5 \\ 1
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                5 \\ -3 \\ -1 
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                -2 \\ 4 \\ 1 
              \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Write a third vector which is linearly independent to the
        first two. (Make sure you show me why it is linearly
        independent.) (6) 
        <ol>
          <li>
            <me>
              \begin{pmatrix}
                1 \\ -6 \\ -2  
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                4 \\ 2 \\ 0 
              \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \begin{pmatrix}
                -8 \\ -2 \\ 1 
              \end{pmatrix},
              \begin{pmatrix}
                -4 \\ -4 \\ -4 
              \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Write equations for these planes.(10) 
        <ol>
          <li>
            The plane with normal 
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              -4 \\ 3 \\ 9 
            \end{pmatrix}</m>
            containing the point
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              0 \\ -4 \\ -2 
            \end{pmatrix}</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The plane containing the points 
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              0 \\ 3 \\ -6 
            \end{pmatrix}, </m>
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              4 \\ -2 \\ -1 
            \end{pmatrix}</m> and 
            <m>\begin{pmatrix}
              -3 \\ -2 \\ 1 
            \end{pmatrix}</m>.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider an affine subspace in <m>\RR^3</m>. Assume that the
        subspace does not include the origin. Prove that the sum of
        any two vectors in the subspace cannot also be in the
        subspace. (One way to do this is by contradiction.) (6) 
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
